class Solution {
    public int integerReplacement(int n) {
        long N = n;
        int count = 0;
        while (N != 1) {
            if (N % 2 == 0) {
                N /= 2;
            } else if (N == 3 || N % 4 == 1) {
                N--;
            } else {
                N++;
            }
            count++;
        }
        return count;
    }
}
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(log n)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The main approach is to use a while loop to iteratively apply the given operations until n becomes 1, utilizing the properties of the numbers to decide whether to increment or decrement n when it's odd. The key strength lies in handling the cases for n being odd and choosing the optimal operation. The use of long for N is to avoid integer overflow for large inputs.
